    "q": "You have the following YAML data file (acl_soth.yml) that defines extended ACLs:\n\nACCESS_LISTS:\n  EXTENDED:\n    - NAME: netconf-operation-challenge-1\n      ENTRIES:\n        - SEQUENCE: 10\n          ACTION: permit\n          PROTOCOL: tcp\n          SOURCE_ANY: true\n          SRC_PORT_OP: gt\n          SRC_PORT: 100\n          DEST_NETWORK: 203.36.36.32\n          DEST_WILDCARD: 0.0.0.15\n          DST_PORT_OP: eq\n          DST_PORT: 636\n        - SEQUENCE: 20\n          ACTION: deny\n          PROTOCOL: ip\n          SOURCE_HOST: 198.51.100.6\n          DEST_ANY: true\n    - NAME: exam2-netconf-create-16\n      ENTRIES:\n        - SEQUENCE: 16\n          ACTION: permit\n          PROTOCOL: udp\n          SOURCE_HOST: 198.51.100.16\n          DEST_HOST: 203.0.113.16\n\nYou need to write a Jinja2 template (config_acl.j2) that renders this YAML into a valid NETCONF XML payload for IOS-XE extended ACLs.\n\nWhich Jinja2 template would correctly render ALL entries from the YAML above?",
    "scenario": "",
    "exp": "📖 Explanation\nThe correct template (A) has proper loop placement and operation scope. Let's walk through the full structure:\n\nSTATIC OUTER WRAPPER:\n• <config>, <native>, <ip>, <access-list> — These are static XML elements that appear once. They never loop because there is only one access-list container on the device. The namespaces (urn:ietf:params:xml:ns:netconf:base:1.0 and Cisco-IOS-XE-native) are declared here.\n\nOUTER LOOP — {% for acl in ACCESS_LISTS.EXTENDED %}:\n• Starts BEFORE <extended> — This is critical. Each iteration creates a SEPARATE <extended> block for each ACL in the YAML (netconf-operation-challenge-1 gets one <extended>, exam2-netconf-create-16 gets another).\n• The loop WRAPS the entire <extended>...</extended> block, so {% endfor %} comes AFTER </extended>.\n\nOPERATION PLACEMENT — nc:operation=\"replace\" on <extended>:\n• Correct scope. Replace at the ACL level means 'this ACL will contain EXACTLY these sequences — delete any sequences on the device not in the YAML.'\n• The xmlns:nc namespace declaration must be on the same element or a parent.\n\nKEY ELEMENT — <name>{{acl.NAME}}</name>:\n• Inside the outer loop, pulling each ACL's NAME from the YAML. This is the key leaf that identifies WHICH ACL to operate on.\n\nINNER LOOP — {% for seq in acl.ENTRIES %}:\n• Starts BEFORE <access-list-seq-rule>. Each iteration creates one rule entry.\n• Nested INSIDE the outer loop, so each ACL gets its own set of rules.\n• The Jinja2 conditionals ({% if seq.SOURCE_ANY %}, {% if seq.SRC_PORT_OP %}, etc.) handle the YANG choice branches — only the elements matching the YAML keys are rendered.\n\nLOOP CLOSURE:\n• {% endfor %} (inner) closes BEFORE </extended> — finishes all rules for this ACL.\n• {% endfor %} (outer) closes AFTER </extended> — moves to the next ACL.\n\n    B → ❌ WRONG LOOP POSITION: The outer loop {% for acl %} starts AFTER <extended>, not before it. This means only ONE <extended> element is ever created, and ALL ACLs' names and rules are dumped inside the same <extended> block. On the second iteration, <name> would be overwritten with exam2-netconf-create-16 while netconf-operation-challenge-1's rules are already inside. Both {% endfor %} tags close together before </extended> — the <extended> tag is never repeated per ACL. Result: invalid XML — multiple <name> keys inside one <extended>, mixed rules from different ACLs.\n\n    C → ❌ WRONG OPERATION PLACEMENT: nc:operation=\"replace\" is on <access-list-seq-rule> instead of <extended>. This changes the behavior completely:\n    • Replace at rule level: replaces INDIVIDUAL sequences but does NOT delete other sequences in the ACL. If the device has sequences 50, 60 that aren't in the YAML, they SURVIVE.\n    • Replace at ACL level (correct): ensures the ACL contains ONLY the sequences in the YAML — sequences 50, 60 would be DELETED.\n    • Also: <extended> has no nc:operation, so it defaults to merge — the ACL itself is never fully replaced, only individual rules within it.\n\n    D → ❌ WRONG OPERATION PLACEMENT (DANGEROUS SCOPE): nc:operation=\"replace\" is on <access-list> — the container that holds ALL ACLs (both standard and extended). Replace at this level means 'the entire access-list container should contain ONLY what I specify.' This would:\n    • DELETE all standard ACLs (none are in the YAML)\n    • DELETE any extended ACLs not in the YAML\n    • Only keep the two ACLs from the YAML\n    The correct scope is per-ACL (<extended>), not the entire container.",
