    "q": "Given this YAML (acl_soth.yml), which is the correct FULL NETCONF XML payload rendered for ACL netconf-operation-challenge-1 with BOTH sequence 10 and sequence 20?\n\nYAML:\n  - NAME: netconf-operation-challenge-1\n    ENTRIES:\n      - SEQUENCE: 10\n        ACTION: permit\n        PROTOCOL: tcp\n        SOURCE_ANY: true\n        SRC_PORT_OP: gt\n        SRC_PORT: 100\n        DEST_NETWORK: 203.36.36.32\n        DEST_WILDCARD: 0.0.0.15\n        DST_PORT_OP: eq\n        DST_PORT: 636\n      - SEQUENCE: 20\n        ACTION: deny\n        PROTOCOL: ip\n        SOURCE_HOST: 198.51.100.6\n        DEST_ANY: true",
    "scenario": "",
    "exp": "📖 Explanation\nThe correct payload (A) renders the full NETCONF XML for ACL 'netconf-operation-challenge-1' with both sequences inside a complete <config> wrapper.\n\nFULL STRUCTURE WALKTHROUGH:\n• <config xmlns=\"urn:ietf:params:xml:ns:netconf:base:1.0\"> — Root element required by NETCONF edit-config RPC. Declares the base NETCONF namespace.\n• <native xmlns=\"http://cisco.com/ns/yang/Cisco-IOS-XE-native\"> — IOS-XE YANG root container. All IOS-XE config lives under this.\n• <ip> → <access-list> — Static path to the ACL container.\n• <extended xmlns=\"http://cisco.com/ns/yang/Cisco-IOS-XE-acl\" nc:operation=\"replace\"> — The ACL list entry with the Cisco ACL namespace. Replace ensures this ACL contains ONLY the sequences specified.\n• <name>netconf-operation-challenge-1</name> — Key leaf identifying WHICH ACL.\n\nSequence 10 — IOS CLI: permit tcp any gt 100 203.36.36.32 0.0.0.15 eq 636\n• <any/> — SOURCE_ANY: true → YANG empty element (self-closing, no content)\n• <src-gt>100</src-gt> — SRC_PORT_OP: gt → source port GREATER THAN 100\n• <dest-ipv4-address>203.36.36.32</dest-ipv4-address> + <dest-mask>0.0.0.15</dest-mask> — DEST_NETWORK + DEST_WILDCARD → network-destination YANG choice (two separate elements)\n• <dst-eq>636</dst-eq> — DST_PORT_OP: eq → destination port EQUAL to 636\n\nSequence 20 — IOS CLI: deny ip host 198.51.100.6 any\n• <host-address>198.51.100.6</host-address> — SOURCE_HOST → host-source YANG choice (single IP, not a subnet)\n• <dst-any/> — DEST_ANY: true → any-destination YANG choice (empty element, self-closing)\n\n    B → ❌ Sequence 10 port operators are SWAPPED: <src-eq>100</src-eq> and <dst-gt>636</dst-gt>. The YAML says SRC_PORT_OP: gt (greater than) and DST_PORT_OP: eq (equal). This would render as 'permit tcp any eq 100 203.36.36.32 0.0.0.15 gt 636' — completely different ACL behavior. Source would match ONLY port 100 instead of ports above 100, and destination would match ports above 636 instead of exactly 636.\n\n    C → ❌ Sequence 20 uses <ipv4-address>198.51.100.6</ipv4-address> — WRONG YANG choice. In the YANG tree, the source has three choices: (1) any-source → <any/>, (2) host-source → <host-address>, (3) network-source → <ipv4-address> + <mask>. SOURCE_HOST maps to host-source, which uses <host-address>. <ipv4-address> is for network-source and REQUIRES a companion <mask> element — without it, the payload is incomplete and may fail or produce unexpected behavior.\n\n    D → ❌ Sequence 20 uses <any/> for destination instead of <dst-any/>. These are DIFFERENT YANG elements in different choice branches: <any/> is under the SOURCE choice (any-source), while <dst-any/> is under the DESTINATION choice (any-destination). Using <any/> in the destination position would set the SOURCE to 'any' (overriding the <host-address>), not the destination. The device would interpret this as 'deny ip any' instead of 'deny ip host 198.51.100.6 any'.",
